Understood — I’ll help Bob (the protagonist / sysadmin) fetch the project member lists and identify infrastructure admins using the GitLab API (non-UI). I don’t yet have the GitLab base URL, so I can’t actually run API calls from here. Below I’ve drafted a short message Bob can use and a compact, safe set of commands he (or I, if he gives me the base URL and permission to run them) can run to:

- get a token from the root credentials (or use a pre-made PAT),
- enumerate projects,
- list project and group members (including inherited),
- flag people who are high-privilege (maintainer/owner) or members of an “infrastructure” group.

Please confirm the GitLab base URL (e.g., https://gitlab.example.com or https://gitlab.internal) and whether you want me to run these commands. If not, Bob can run them locally.

Message draft to Bob (direct, step-by-step) plus concrete commands:

1) Try to obtain a private token (session) from root credentials
- Replace GITLAB_URL with your GitLab base URL.
- If session endpoint is disabled, create a personal access token (Admin -> User -> Access Tokens) with api scope and use that instead.

Example (attempt session token):
TOKEN=$(curl -s --insecure -X POST "https://GITLAB_URL/api/v4/session" \
  -d "login=root&password=theagentcompany" | jq -r '.private_token')

If TOKEN is empty or endpoint not available, create a PAT for root or another admin and set:
TOKEN=your_personal_access_token_here

2) List accessible projects (show id and path)
curl -s --insecure --header "PRIVATE-TOKEN: $TOKEN" \
  "https://GITLAB_URL/api/v4/projects?order_by=id&per_page=100" | \
  jq -r '.[] | "\(.id)\t\(.path_with_namespace)"'

(If you have many projects, iterate pages with &page=N or use pagination logic.)

3) Get a project's members (including inherited) and show role names
Replace PROJECT_ID with the numeric id from step 2.

curl -s --insecure --header "PRIVATE-TOKEN: $TOKEN" \
  "https://GITLAB_URL/api/v4/projects/PROJECT_ID/members/all?per_page=100" | \
  jq -r '.[] |
    (.username // "<no-username>") as $u |
    (.name // "<no-name>") as $n |
    (.access_level) as $al |
    ($al | if .==50 then "Owner" elif .==40 then "Maintainer" elif .==30 then "Developer" elif .==20 then "Reporter" else "Guest" end) as $role |
    "\($u)\t\($n)\t\($al)\t\($role)"'

- access_level mapping: 50=Owner, 40=Maintainer, 30=Developer, 20=Reporter, 10=Guest.

4) Find groups named like "infrastructure" and list their members
Search groups:
curl -s --insecure --header "PRIVATE-TOKEN: $TOKEN" \
  "https://GITLAB_URL/api/v4/groups?search=infrastructure&per_page=100" | jq

If you find an infra group id (GROUP_ID), list members (including inherited):
curl -s --insecure --header "PRIVATE-TOKEN: $TOKEN" \
  "https://GITLAB_URL/api/v4/groups/GROUP_ID/members/all?per_page=100" | \
  jq -r '.[] | "\(.username)\t\(.name)\t\(.access_level) \(.access_level|if .==50 then \"Owner\" elif .==40 then \"Maintainer\" elif .==30 then \"Developer\" elif .==20 then \"Reporter\" else \"Guest\" end)"'

Infrastructure admins are typically:
- members of an infrastructure group (e.g., group name contains infra, infrastructure, platform),
- or project members with access_level >= 40 (Maintainer or Owner),
- or users with is_admin=true (site admins) — can be listed only with admin privileges:
curl -s --insecure --header "PRIVATE-TOKEN: $TOKEN" \
  "https://GITLAB_URL/api/v4/users?per_page=100&active=true" | \
  jq -r '.[] | select(.is_admin==true) | "\(.username)\t\(.name)\t is_admin: \(.is_admin)"'

5) Quick script to list all projects and show high-privilege members (owner/maintainer)
TOKEN=...; GITLAB=https://GITLAB_URL
curl -s --insecure --header "PRIVATE-TOKEN: $TOKEN" "$GITLAB/api/v4/projects?per_page=100" \
  | jq -r '.[].id' \
  | while read pid; do
      echo "Project $pid:"
      curl -s --insecure --header "PRIVATE-TOKEN: $TOKEN" \
        "$GITLAB/api/v4/projects/$pid/members/all?per_page=100" \
        | jq -r '.[] | select(.access_level>=40) | "\(.username)\t\(.name)\t\(.access_level) \(
            if .access_level==50 then "Owner" elif .access_level==40 then "Maintainer" else .access_level end
          )"'
    done

Notes, considerations, and caveats
- If your GitLab uses a self-signed certificate, --insecure lets curl proceed; replace with valid CA bundle in production.
- The session endpoint (POST /api/v4/session) may be disabled depending on GitLab version or configuration. If so, create a PAT manually and use PRIVATE-TOKEN header.
- Pagination: if you have many projects/users, you must iterate pages (page=N & per_page=100) or use Link headers.
- The definition of “infrastructure admin” can vary. The commands above find:
  - group members of an "infrastructure" group (if present),
  - project-level maintainers/owners (access_level >= 40),
  - site-level admins (is_admin true).
  If you want a stricter definition (e.g., only site admins, or only members of group "infra"), tell me which.
- Using root credentials has risk; prefer a scoped PAT for auditing.

Next steps
- Provide the GitLab base URL (https://...).
- Tell me whether you want me to run the commands from here (I’ll run them with the provided root credentials) or whether you prefer to run them locally and paste results.
- Tell me your definition of “infrastructure admin” if you want a different rule than the one above.

Shall I proceed and query the GitLab instance now (please confirm the base URL)?
